{
  "answer": "**In \"The Husband's Message\" (chapter 8 of *Old English Elegies*), the speaker is a wooden beam carved with runes by the exiled husband to send a secret message to his wife.**[^1]\n\n**The runes specifically convey his command—via the wood's voice—to urge her to action: she must set out to sea southward as soon as she hears the cuckoo's mournful call from the hillside grove in springtime.**[^2] **No living person should delay her or obstruct her journey; she is to seek the sea (\"the gull's homeland\"), board a sea-boat (\"sænacan\"), and travel \"over the sea-road\" (\"merelade\") until she finds him waiting there among a foreign people.**[^3]\n\n**This plea frames her journey as fulfilling their former vows (\"wordbeotunga\") made in the mead-halls, with the runes ᛋᚱᛠᚹᛞ (sigel-rād-ēar-wynn-dæg, glossed as \"Sun-Ride, Sea-Joy, Day\") swearing his enduring oath to their \"loving troth\" (\"winetreowe\").**[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 8 (\"Nu ic onsundran...\"), translation, [full chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/08-nu-ic-onsundran-the-secgan-wille-treocyn-ic-tudre-/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., [p-58bec2](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/08-nu-ic-onsundran-the-secgan-wille-treocyn-ic-tudre-/translation/#p-58bec2): \"He himself now bids me / joyfully urge you to stir the sea-way, / as soon as you hear on the slope's edge / the grieving cuckoo cry in the grove.\"\n\n[^3]: Ibid.: \"Let no living man then hold you back, / delay your leaving, hinder your path. / Begin to seek the sea, the gull's homeland, / board a sea-boat, so that south from here / over the sea-road you may find the man, / where your prince is waiting for you.\"\n\n[^4]: Ibid.: \"I join together ᛋ and ᚱ, / and ᛠ, ᚹ, and ᛞ to name in an oath / [Sun-Ride, Sea-Joy, Day] / that he the pledge and the loving troth, / while he is living, wishes to keep.\"",
